{
  "texts": [
    "Among these, phasor-based methods are often preferred because they are straightforward to implement, interpretable, and compatible with existing measurement infrastructures [5].Within phasor-based methods, single-ended schemes use only local measurements to estimate the fault distance.",
    "Common methods include the impedance method [6], the reactance method [7], and Takagi-type methods [8], [5], [9].",
    "Twoended schemes extend this approach by using synchronized measurements at both line terminals and, therefore, require a communications link.",
    "The main studies include [10], [11], [12], [13].",
    "Despite this variety, phasor-based methodologies are grounded in standard short-circuit assumptions associated with synchronous-machine behavior.Motivated by these limitations, recent literature has begun to explicitly account for IBR effects in fault-location algorithms."
  ]
}